**Clinical Reasoning:**
The patient's occupational exposure to birds, combined with his episodic symptoms worsening after work and diffuse lower lung involvement on CXR, strongly suggest bird fancier's pneumonia (avian tuberculosis-like illness due to *Mycobacterium avium* complex or similar organisms). Although PPD was negative, environmental exposure remains key. Avoidance of birds would prevent ongoing antigenic stimulation and halt progression. No indication supports treating with anti-TB drugs (isoniazid) given no active TB infection confirmed. Inhaled corticosteroids (beclomethasone) might help if there were significant airflow obstruction but aren't first-line here. Thoracocentesis isn’t indicated without pleural effusion. Thus, avoiding exposure is primary.

